pub1_title: Impacts of climate and vegetation change on carbon accumulation in a south-central Alaskan peatland assessed with novel organic geochemical techniques
paleoDataNotes: "While neither of these calibrations seems to reconstruct reasonable range of temperatures for the Holocene – both calibrations reconstruct a range of temperatures for the Holocene that exceeds 6°C – the shifts in temperature we reconstruct are broadly consistent with changes in glacial ice extent documented throughout south-central Alaska (Figure 6). This consistency suggests that the MBT/CBT temperature estimates, although incorrect in overall magnitude, may change in a manner consistent with Holocene temperature change."
QC comments: authors reconstruct temperature using two calibrations, and display and interpret both records equally in this paper. Neither reconstruction accurately representes the magnidute of temprature change.  For this database, we set "units" = "relative T" to encode the limitations described by the original authors.

pub1_authors: Larocque-Tobler, Isabelle; Heiri, Oliver; Wehrli, Michael
pub1_title: Late Glacial and Holocene temperature changes at Egelsee, Switzerland, reconstructed using subfossil chironomids
paleoDataNotes: Earlier version of Swiss transfer function described in Heiri, Lotter 2010 (DOI 10.1007/s10933-010-9439-z). Some samples characterized by low counts, some samples dated based on extrapolation, top two samples with many semi-terrestrial taxa, not reliable; strong local human impact (grazing, Cannabis) from ca. 1500 cal BP onwards. Data for only one of the reconstructions described in this paper were available. Chronology recalculated 3.5.2019 by OHE based on data in Wehrli et al. 10.1177/0959683607080515

paleoDataNotes: Calibration of d180 to temperature was made with a second order polynom, and constrained to fit the borehole temperature profile. T=-211.4(°C)-11.88(°C/‰)*delta-0.1925(°C/‰^2)*delta^2. It corresponds to a temeprature sensitivity of 1.67°C/‰ for the holocene, and 4.33‰/°C for the LGMT. Elevation change needs to be taken into account in addition.

paleoDataNotes: In looking at the data a bit more closely, I see that there is quite a big difference between our reconstructed July temperatre near the top of the core (~5.7 C) and observed temperatre (9.2 C, based on an earlier publication, and ~12 C, based on the website link you sent. This offset is large and it may be because our modern training set is biased toward more northern (and hence colder) samples. In this regard I think the reconstruction may be systematically too cold, but the relative changes are probably reliable. Perhaps anomalies should be calculated?

QC comments: Record of pluvials with an annual/winter season interpretation "These conditions include a significantly southward displaced, winter season polar front jet stream, its associated storm tracks, and moisture transport from the tropical North Pacific. Moreover, these conditions must persist on a near annual (winter season) basis for the duration of the lake            s existence. To develop and maintain decadal-to-multi-centennial scale lakes in the Mojave River sink requires atmospheric conditions that generate higher- than-average winter precipitation across the region on a recur- ring annual basis."

pub1_title: Deglacial Indian monsoon failure and North Atlantic stadials linked by Indian Ocean surface cooling
calibration_method: Calibration: Sonzogni et al. 1997 Quaternary Research. This is written about seasonality: Foraminiferal, coccolithophorid, and alkenone fluxes all reach their maximum in the Arabian Sea during the summer monsoon season of June–September [28, 29, 30], suggesting that both Mg/Ca-δ18O and UK′ might preferentially record temperatures during this season. However, G. ruber grow throughout the year, and are the dominant foraminiferal species during the intermonsoon and winter monsoon seasons [31]. The differences in the UK′ and Mg/Ca-δ18O estimates during the Early Holocene epoch may therefore reflect a slight difference in seasonal averaging. The UK′ data indicate cooler SSTs during the early Holocene, consistent with mean annual TraCE data (Fig. 1b). Independent evidence for an orbitally-driven enhancement in monsoon-driven upwelling [32] suggests that cooler temperatures might be expected during the upwelling season, with potential to influence the annual mean. In contrast, the Mg/Ca-δ18O data clearly suggest a warmer early Holocene (Fig. 1a). Conceivably, this might represent a bias to the intermonsoon season, when model simulations suggest warmer western Indian Ocean SSTs occur due to a latent heat feedback associated with stronger monsoon winds over land [33].
QC comments: this Temp12k record is superseded by a Bayesian-based calibration;

paleoDataNotes: New multivariate calibration developed for this study; see Supplementary Information. The Mg/Ca aliquots were cleaned using the full reductive and oxidative protocol described by Boyle & Keigwin [9] as modified by Barker et al. [10], including additional clay removal with methanol/MilliQ water rinses. This is written about seasonality: Foraminiferal, coccolithophorid, and alkenone fluxes all reach their maximum in the Arabian Sea during the summer monsoon season of June–September [28, 29, 30], suggesting that both Mg/Ca-δ18O and UK′ might preferentially record temperatures during this season. However, G. ruber grow throughout the year, and are the dominant foraminiferal species during the intermonsoon and winter monsoon seasons [31]. The differences in the UK′ and Mg/Ca-δ18O estimates during the Early Holocene epoch may therefore reflect a slight difference in seasonal averaging. The UK′ data indicate cooler SSTs during the early Holocene, consistent with mean annual TraCE data (Fig. 1b). Independent evidence for an orbitally-driven enhancement in monsoon-driven upwelling [32] suggests that cooler temperatures might be expected during the upwelling season, with potential to influence the annual mean. In contrast, the Mg/Ca-δ18O data clearly suggest a warmer early Holocene (Fig. 1a). Conceivably, this might represent a bias to the intermonsoon season, when model simulations suggest warmer western Indian Ocean SSTs occur due to a latent heat feedback associated with stronger monsoon winds over land [33]. LJ: but flux-weighted temperatures of G. ruber in the Arabian Sea are very close to annual mean (Jonkers & Kucera 2015, Biogeosciences), so set to annual
QC comments: this Temp12k record is superseded by a Bayesian-based calibration; seasonality ambiguous according to authors, used expert judgement (see notes)

pub1_authors: Risebrobakken, Bj  rg; Dokken, Trond; Smedsrud, Lars Henrik; Andersson, Carin; Jansen, Eystein; Moros, Matthias; Ivanova, Elena V.
pub1_title: Early Holocene temperature variability in the Nordic Seas: The role of oceanic heat advection versus changes in orbital forcing
QC comments: Following a northward oceanic heat release [Skagseth et al., 2008], higher δ18O are expected northward if solely influenced by temperature. This is not the case 12–8.5 ka BP; lower δ18O are recorded in the SW Barents Sea and at the Voering Plateau than in the Faroe‐Shetland Channel (Figure 5). Accordingly, low‐salinity water influenced the Voering Plateau and SW Barents Sea 12–8.5 ka BP, with a gradually diminishing effect (Figure 5). LJ: exact end of salinity changes not made explicit, the authors mention that d18O may reflect the Holocene thermal optimum. I think that only the younger part of this record may meet the criteria, if at all

paleoDataNotes: One-component model using Barley et al. 2006 calibration data set. Temperature reconstruction contains a splice of data from two cores, taken at two different water depths (see original paper for descriptions); this allowed for a continuous reconstruction from early to late Holocene. Chronology provided only for bottom ("deep-water") core: this choice was made for consistency with the previous database (see www.ncdc.noaa.gov/paleo/study/15444), which we are treating as the previous formal "publication" of this spliced temperature reconstruction.
QC comments: fails age control, barely; accepted because chronology is solid

pub1_authors: Berke, Melissa A.; Johnson, Thomas C.; Werne, Josef P.; Grice, Kliti; Schouten, Stefan; Sinninghe Damst̩, Jaap S.
pub1_title: Molecular records of climate variability and vegetation response since the Late Pleistocene in the Lake Victoria basin, East Africa
paleoDataNotes: TEX86-inferred temperature only reliable from 15.2 to 1 ka, prior to that GDGTs influenced by soil input. Justification from the paper to use the marine calibration curve at this lake site: "Lake Victoria surface sediment samples plot anomalously warm in the global lake calibration plot (Powers et al., 2010), but yield LST similar to those of present day when using the global marine calibration line (Kim et al., 2010). We speculate that a calibration offset for Lake Victoria may be due to a lack of a permanent chemocline and anoxic deep water, similar to that of Lake Turkana, which also shows surface sediments that plot on the warm side of the global lake calibration curve and fit the marine TEX86 calibration curve (Berke et al., 2012). Thaumarchaeota are known to be ammonia oxidizers (Konneke et al., 2005; Wuchter et al., 2006) and therefore may be nourished by the proximity of an oxic and anoxic water boundary where turbulent mixing can provide an ample supply of ammonia across the chemocline (Konneke et al., 2005; Coolen et al., 2007; Blaga et al., 2011). In the absence of such conditions, such as in the oceans and in Lake Victoria, a different community of Thaumarchaea may dominate and generate GDGTs that more closely tracks the marine TEX86 calibration curve."
